# RISKS.md

> This document should always answer: what could invalidate PDE, and how would we know early?

Each risk includes: what it is, why it matters, how we would detect it, and what would reduce it. Risks are ordered by how likely they are to kill the project, not by how interesting they are to discuss.

---

## R1 — The sensor/product paradox

**What it is**

Mini apps are framed as sensors, not products. But a mini app with no standalone value gets no usage, and a mini app with no usage generates no signal. The framing risks hiding the fact that the first mini app still has to win as a product before it can function as a sensor.

**Why it matters**

This is the same cold-start problem the Super App version had, relabeled. If we design the first mini app assuming it only needs to be "good enough to collect signal," we will build something nobody opens twice.

**How we would detect it**

Weekly retention of the first mini app is at or below what any generic, non-personalized app in that category would get. Users open it once out of curiosity and don't return.

**What would reduce it**

Build and evaluate the first mini app exactly as if PDE and the Interest Graph did not exist — as a standalone product that has to win purely on its own value. Only instrument it for cross-domain signal once it has retention on its own merits.

**Status:** Unresolved. This is the single most important open risk in the project.

