## R2 — Scope expansion disguised as strategic clarity

**What it is**

The repository structure (VISION, INTEREST_GRAPH, TECHNICAL_ARCHITECTURE, DATABASE, AI, BUSINESS_MODEL, ROADMAP, USER_RESEARCH...) is the documentation footprint of a funded, staffed startup. We are two people with 15h/week each.

**Why it matters**

Writing strategy is lower-risk and more comfortable than talking to users, because it can't "fail" the way a real conversation can. It is easy to spend most of our available hours refining documents instead of testing the core hypothesis with real people.

**How we would detect it**

Time spent per week on documentation/architecture exceeds time spent per week talking to users or building the first testable thing. Weeks pass with new docs but no new user conversations or usage data.

**What would reduce it**

A simple time-allocation rule: no work on INTEREST_GRAPH.md, TECHNICAL_ARCHITECTURE.md, or AI.md until the user problem (cost of evaluating options) has been validated with real behavioral evidence, not just conversations.

**Status:** Live risk. Worth checking honestly every 2-3 weeks: where did the hours actually go?

