## R3 — Privacy and profiling exposure (GDPR)

**What it is**

The core asset — a unified behavioral model of a person across unrelated domains (what they watch, eat, buy, read) — is, under GDPR, profiling in one of its most sensitive forms. This is structurally different from a single-domain recommendation system.

**Why it matters**

Combining data across domains this different typically requires explicit, granular consent rather than legitimate interest. Article 22 GDPR gives users rights against decisions based solely on automated processing with significant effects — the more "decision-making" PDE presents itself as, the closer it sits to that threshold. Two people at 15h/week are not equipped to absorb a serious compliance failure.

**How we would detect it**

We can't wait to "detect" this reactively — it needs review before storing cross-domain personal data at any real scale, not after.

**What would reduce it**

Legal review (even a single paid consultation) before building any cross-domain data model. Design data collection to be domain-siloed and opt-in per domain from day one, rather than assuming a unified profile is the default.

**Status:** Unresolved, not yet addressed anywhere in the repository.

