## R6 — Structural competition from platforms that already have the data

**What it is**

Google, Amazon, and Meta already hold cross-domain behavioral data about their own users (search, maps, shopping, social) and have not unified it into a "personal decision engine." This is evidence the problem is structurally hard — internal business silos, regulatory exposure, and public trust risk — not evidence that the opportunity is simply unclaimed.

**Why it matters**

If we succeed at building real cross-domain signal and it becomes commercially interesting, it becomes interesting to platforms with orders of magnitude more data and distribution than us. We should not assume "nobody has done this yet" implies "nobody could do this quickly if it worked."

**How we would detect it**

Ongoing competitive monitoring once any traction appears — not a one-time check now.

**What would reduce it**

Depth in a narrow, defensible niche (data or trust that big platforms have no incentive to replicate cheaply) rather than breadth across many domains, at least until there is real traction to defend.

**Status:** Background risk, low urgency now, high urgency if R1 and R5 are resolved positively.

---

## R7 — Part-time execution risk

**What it is**

All of the above has to be resolved with 15h/week per person, alongside full-time jobs. This is not a risk specific to PDE, but it compounds every other risk on this list — less time means slower learning cycles on R1, R4, and R5, and more temptation toward R2 (documentation instead of testing).

**Why it matters**

Every week spent without new evidence (usage data or user conversations) is a week where the biggest risks on this list remain exactly as uncertain as they are today.

**How we would detect it**

Track weeks-since-last-new-evidence as a simple internal metric. If this number keeps growing, something on this list is being avoided.

**What would reduce it**

A hard rule: each 2-week cycle must produce at least one piece of new evidence (a user conversation, a usage metric, a test result) — not just a new document.

**Status:** Ongoing, structural, will not go away.

---

## How to use this document

Before writing PRODUCT.md or MVP.md in detail, re-read R1 and R2. They are the two risks most likely to quietly redirect effort away from what actually needs validating first: whether a single mini app, evaluated purely as a product, can win real and repeated usage.
